    <div class="crypto-info">
        <h2>What it is ?</h2>
        <p class="">
            Cryptocurrency is a general term for a digital medium that is capable of moving
            either funds or information (sometimes both) to basically anywhere on the planet with an
            internet connection; without reliance on a trusted 3rd party. Although no physical tranfer
            of a material occurs, crypto currencies “move” on the blockchain
            where the transactions is stored in an immutable form free for all to see.
            <br />
            Cryptocurrencies exist only digitally and, as of yet, have no physical or “cash” correspondent
            as most traditional currencies do. They are often referred to as “tokens” or “coins” but this
            is really just an arbitrary designation given to a discrete unit of digital information based
            on peoples’ ingrained thinking toward currency. There may be some similarities between
            cryptocurrencies and what is held on the computers of banks and financial institutions as
            “cash in digital form” but they are hardly ever more than surface deep. The term “crypto”,
            although not the most accurate, refers to how the majority of cryptocurrencies are encrypted/embedded
            into the “blockchain” (the network on which they move about). This means that their every movement is
            made both highly known and secure; although, to a large degree, the end-users on each transaction remain
            anonymous. The addition of the term “currency” probably stems from the fact that the original cryptocurrency, Bitcoin,
            was intended to be a “purely peer-to-peer version of electronic cash” with which individuals could make
            financial transactions without relying on a “trusted 3rd party”.

