    <div class="crypto-info">
        <h2>Where they stand ?</h2>
        <p>
            As it is today, cryptocurrencies exist in an unregulated kind of gray zone; at least as far as 
            the big financial institutions and governments of the world are concerned. They are not officially
            recognized as currencies per se, but have seen an enormous rise in interest and popularity among 
            an increasing number of people who recognize their potential. There is still some debate among 
            the global community and certain regulatory bodies alike as to how they should be classified, 
            For the time being, cryptocurrencies can best be thought of as something like a combination of a 
            security and a stock in a company. However, speaking truly, they occupy their own unique, and as 
            yet, unprecedented category. They are very much the type of technology that, like the internet, 
            will likely end up forcing the world to adapt to it rather than them adapting to the world.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="crypto-info">
        <h2>Are cryptocurrencies money ?</h2>
        <p>
            Although the term “currency” may limit one’s impression of cryptocurrencies to simple financial
            transactions there is actually a wide variety of different types of cryptocurrencies with a huge
            variety of intended uses; almost none of which are the same. Some are designed purely to support
            financial transactions. Others to facilitate the secure transfer of information via “smart contracts” .
            Some are limited to a very narrow spectrum of uses while others are almost unlimited. Some, like Ripple (XRP),
            are highly centralized while others like Bitcoin (BTC) and Ethereum (ETH) are completely decentralized.
            There are even some cryptocurrencies like Bitqy (BQ) which are the creation of a single company seeking to
            build value in their coin via their networking efforts and special offers with other companies. A common trend
            is that a need will either be identified or presumed to exist and a cryptocurrency will be designed to serve it.
            This makes the nature of cryptocurrency markets a very interesting one, indeed. It is quite difficult to imagine
            any other frontier where such a combination of technology and creativity is converging quite so strongly.
            <br />
            Most cryptocurrencies do retain some monetary value tradeable on the exchanges so it is not true to 
            say they don’t. However, many of them are almost like a currency/stock hybrid in that they represent
            not only an assigned monetary value but also a unique function built in to them by the team that 
            designed them. Even this comparison, however, is not quite accurate as cryptocurrencies do not fit 
            the same profile as stock in a company either. They are truly an entirely new commodity the likes of
            which has never been seen before. Further, there currently doesn’t seem to be a limit for the 
            different uses and purposes a cryptocurrency can be designed for. And here, in 2018, it must be 
            admitted that there is a kind of free for all mentality concerning the cryptocurrency market as 
            they are a technology that is both extremely new and unproven while showing tremendous potential. 
            It is not yet quite clear what needs will be met and what trends will truly take off over others in 
            the future of the crypto world. It is widely assumed, however, just given the sheer numbers that 
            things are most definitely afoot in terms of the development and adoption of these technologies and 
            going back to the world before cryptocurrency seems increasingly unlikely. So, the comparison to the 
            dot com bubble is definitely an apt one.
        </p>
