                    Transactions with cryptocurrencies are : <br />
                    <strong>Extremely fast:</strong> A typical international transfer made with a bank may take up to a week and involve
                    sometimes numerous fees along the way. With a typical cryptocurrency transaction, it generally takes
                    from 1 to 30 minutes and there will only be a single fee, if any. There are cases, however, when
                    the network is particularly busy when a transaction may take several days. At these times,
                    transaction fees may temporarily rise. However, this is still far faster and cheaper than other
                    methods. Newer cryptocurrency and network models are only making things faster and simpler as the
                    technology improves.
                    <br />
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="crypto-info">
                <p>
                    <strong>Made from peer to peer:</strong> As it is today, almost all transfers involve a 3rd party
                    service. This may come in the form of a bank, a credit card company or a service like PayPal. There
                    is nothing particularly wrong with this but it does have some drawbacks. First and foremost is a
                    lack of security. It may not be widely publicized but such companies and services are the relentless
                    targets of fraud, hacking and other criminal attempts at access. They spend huge amounts of money to
                    maintain security and loss prevention and they are not always successful. There is therefore no way
                    for them to avoid charging fees and causing endless inconveniences simply for either holding your
                    money or moving it for you. Despite their popularity, the banking system is tremendously inefficient
                    and outdated. Further, the general lack of control and free access to your funds in a bank is done
                    away with in using crypto currencies. Your funds are yours and may be transferred, deposited and
                    stored as easily as photos on an email. While in the bank, your funds are not truly yours and your
                    access to them may be severely delayed or denied altogether based on the whims of whatever
                    institution is holding them. You will also likely be paying considerable fees for often bizarre and
                    arbitrary reasons about which you can do nothing.
                    <br />
                </p>
